sec.p:
In our previous studies, two-dimensional (2D) heterojunction with independent and separated oxidation and reduction centers have revealed great potential in photo-catalyzed water splitting, CO2 reduction, and photo-induced cancer catalytic therapy30–34. Specifically, the separated electrons in the conduction band (CB) of one catalyst with high reduction potential are able to catalyze various reduction reactions, such as O2/·O2−, CO2/CO, O2/H2O2, et al., meanwhile, the separated holes in the valence band (VB) of the other catalyst with high oxidation potential also have ability to mediated diverse oxidation reactions, such as GSH/GSSG, OH−/·OH, H2O/O2, et al. Therefore, 2D heterojunction with ability to realize reduction and oxidation reactions synchronously provides an alternative detour strategy for some reactions, which are difficult to be realized in one step, for example, in situ generation of H2O2 through two-step circuitous strategy (H2O−h+O2-e−H2O2)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
